@node "Vehicle" "What is a Vehicle?"

A  vehicle  is something the player and directly control in the game.  This
can  be anything from a single little man (or woman) to a huge galaxy-class
starship.

Since a vehicle is controllable by the player, various variables need to be
set to make each vehicle individual.  These variables are explained below:

 Variable      | Range     | Description
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Name          |           | The name for this vehicle.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Max. Speed    | 0 - 500   | The maximum speed this vehicle can travel at.
               |           | You can set this to zero to make the vehicle,
               |           | for example, a stationary turret.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Crew Needed   | 0 - 8     | How many crew members the vehicle needs to
               |           | operate.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Max. Armour   | 0% - 200% | The percentage of armour this vehicle is
               |           | allowed.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Maintenance   | $500-5000 | How much it costs to repair the vehicle for
               |           | an extra 25% of armour per maintenance.  In
               |           | the game, if the vehicle has 77% the vehicle
               |           | cannot be repaired until it has less than 75%.
               |           | It's just nasty, that's all :)
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Water Mode    |           | What type(s) of water can the vehicle use.
               |           | These are:
               |           | - "Not Allowed": loses armour when in water
               |           | - "Shallow Only": OK in shallow else lose arm.
               |           | - "Water Only": must be in non-shallow water
               |           | - "Any": okay in any situation
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Crew Level    |           | What level/rank the crew must have achieved
               |           | before they can use this vehicle (and
               |           | therefore the player can use).  These are:
               |           | - "Any": doesn't matter
               |           | - "Captian/Major/General & Up": obvious really
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Can Fly       | Yes/No    | Can this vehicle fly?  If yes...
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Can Land      | Yes/No    | ... can the vehicle land?  If not, it crashes
               |           | when it hits ground.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Weapon        |           | What weapon does this vehicle have when it is
               |           | first built.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------

@endnode

@node "Weapon" "What is a Weapon?"

Strangely enough, a weapon in FUBAR is much like a weapon in real life - an
object or instrument used in fighting.  A weapon can be anything from a pea
shooter to a huge 20,000 gigatonne nuclear weapon.

As with a vehicle, a weapon also has variables.  These are listed below
with their descriptions:

 Variable      | Range     | Description
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Name          |           | Name of the weapon.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Range         | 10%-200%  | The maximum range of the weapon before it
               |           | hits the ground or disintegrates.  This is
               |           | how far, in a relative position expressed as
               |           | a percentage, the weapon can glide through the
               |           | air or water.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Accuracy      | 5% - 100% | The ratio on how exact - depending on other
               |           | factors - the weapon hits its approximated
               |           | target.  Such factors could be wind, gravity,
               |           | etc..
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Self-exploding| Yes/No &  | Whether or not the weapon is self-exploding.
               | 1 - 10s   | If it is, a delay expressed in seconds, is 
               |           | counted after which the weapon will explode.
               |           | If it is not, the weapon will reach its
               |           | target and do nothing.  There is a random
               |           | factor on this when the game runs, as to
               |           | such whether or not the weapon becomes a dud.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Explode on    | Yes/No    | Should the weapon explode when it hits
 Impact        |           | something (could be anything not necessarily
               |           | its designated target) or whether it should
               |           | always hit its target.  If it should always
               |           | hit the target, the weapon will attempt to
               |           | adjust its course to hit the target.  If
               |           | Homes-in on Target is selected as well, the
               |           | more accurate the weapon is at getting a
               |           | better lock on the target.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Cause Shrapnel| Yes/No    | When the weapon explodes, should tiny pieces
               |           | of it be thrown into the air, damaging
               |           | anything the shrapnel cares to hit.  The
               |           | damage varies between 2% to 7%.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Chemical      | Yes/No    | DO NOT USE - RESERVED.
 Weapon        |           |
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Nuclear       | Yes/No    | DO NOT USE - RESERVED.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------
 Homes-in on   | Yes/No    | Used chiefly in conjunction with Explode on
 Target        |           | Impact.
---------------+-----------+-----------------------------------------------

@endnode

@node "Map" "What is a Map?"

A map is a level map.  So, what's a level map?

A  level  map is simply an arrangement of @{" images " link "Image" 0} that represent a country
in a World map.  Many games use them to create the scenery and surroundings
of a level.

A  map  is  divided  up  into  tiles, which is a 16 by 16 pixel square with
various  properties  attached  to  each  tile.  Each tile has the following
properties:

 Property        | Description
-----------------+---------------------------------------------------------
 Image           | A graphical @{" image " link "Image" 0} of the specific tile on the map.
-----------------+---------------------------------------------------------
 Surface         | Defines each tile as to what type of area it is, for
                 | example, grass, water, snow, swamp, etc..
-----------------+---------------------------------------------------------

@{i}BETA NOTE:  This property list may grow in future beta releases.@{ui}

On  the World map, there are @{" countries " link "Country" 0}.  Each country is assigned a level
map,  upon  which  the battle between two players occurs - that's how level
map and World maps are linked.

@endnode

@node "Country" "What is a Country?"

In  the actual game, each player must try to conquer the whole World.  This
is  done  by capturing each individual country, which may be owned by other
players.   Each  player  must have at least one country, otherwise they are
declared non-existant.

From  a  CC  point  of view, each country is assoicated with a @{" level map " link "Map" 0}.
Each   country  also  has  various  characteristics,  for  example  weather
settings,  day/night  times,  number of resources, its cities and villages,
etc..

@{i}BETA NOTE:  This section will be expanded.@{ui}

@endnode

@node "Image" "What is an Image?"

An  image is basically a small picture, which can be up to 32 by 32 pixels.
Paint packages also call them brushes.

In  the  CC,  there  is  a  thing  called  an Image Bank.  This is really a
collection  of  200  or  so  different  images,  all  using the same colour
palette.  Every image can be used in @{" object " link "Object" 0}, @{" vehicle " link "Vehicle" 0} and @{" weapon " link "Weapon" 0} animations,
tile graphics for @{" level maps " link "Map" 0}, and for placing on the World map itself.

Image  examples  could  be for 10 frames of animation for a tree blowing in
the  window,  or  a  single image for a tank driving across the floor, or a
bird flying in the air, etc..

See the Image Bank documentation for more information about image banks.

@endnode

