 Palette Editor
---------------------------------------------------
                     Colours
 +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+
 |@{bg fill}   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   @{bg background}|
 |@{bg fill}   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   @{bg background}|
 |@{bg fill}   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   @{bg background}|
 +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+

   Red <@{bg fill}-------------------|------------------@{bg background}> 7
 Green <@{bg fill}-----------------------|--------------@{bg background}> 9
  Blue <@{bg fill}-------------------------------------|@{bg background}> 15
                   Mode < @ | 4-bit (OCS/ECS) >

 |@{bg fill}    Load...    @{bg background}| |@{bg fill}    Save...    @{bg background}| |@{bg fill}   Reset   @{bg background}|
 |@{bg fill}     Okay      @{bg background}|                   |@{bg fill}   Cancel  @{bg background}|
---------------------------------------------------

(Things you can click on are marked @{bg fill}like this@{bg background}.)

@{b}Colours:@{ub}   These  are  all the colours available on the screen which can be
changed.

@{b}Red:@{ub}   Changing  this  changes  the  amount of red there is in the selected
colour.

@{b}Green:@{ub}   Changing this changes the amount of green there is in the selected
colour.

@{b}Blue:@{ub}   Changing  this  changes the amount of blue there is in the selected
colour.  (You get the idea by now, don't you?  :)

@{b}Mode:@{ub}   This  allows  you to swap between 4-bit and 8-bit colour addressing
modes.   You  cannot  use  this, unless you have a graphics card or the AGA
chipset.   Using  8-bit  addressing  allows  you to access the Amiga's 16.7
million colour palette, whereas 4-bit addressing allows only 4096.

@{i}BETA NOTE:  Since the CC doesn't directly support AGA just yet, this gadget
is disabled.  Give it time..  :)@{ui}

Load:  This pops up a file requester, asking you to select a palette file.

You can load a palette from any of the following files:

 · A normal palette file, saved as in a paint package.
 · An IFF image - be it a picture, brush, etc..
 · Any  IFF  animation  (in  this  case, the palette will be taken from the
first frame)

If  you  supply  a  file  which  the  CC can't instantly recognise, it will
attempt  to examine the file a bit better.  If that fails, it won't be able
to find any palette data, and you will be told and the operation cancelled.

@{i}BETA  NOTE:   Again,  hopefully  datatypes will be supported here for OS3.x
users.@{ui}

@{b}Save@{ub}
This will save a standard IFF ILBM palette file, with the name given at the
file requester this function pops up.

@{b}Reset@{ub}
Any changes made to the colours will be reset to when this window was first
opened when this button is clicked.

@{b}Okay@{ub}
Keeps the changes.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
Forgets the changes, and restores the original palette.

@endnode

@node "WMapImportG" "Import Graphic - World Map Editor"

This allows you to import a graphic to use as the graphical representation for
the World in the actual game.

This image can be any non 24-bit image (up to 256 colours), and will be
used in the main game.

To achieve this, the CC opens a dialog box:

-------------------------------------
 Import Graphic
-------------------------------------
 Image  |@{bg fill}______________________@{bg background}||@{bg fill} ? @{bg background}|

 +---------------------------------+
 |    <@{bg fill} X @{bg background}> Use Files Palette      |
 |    <@{bg fill} X @{bg background}> Adapt Screen           |
 +---------------------------------+

 |@{bg fill} Import @{bg background}|               |@{bg fill} Cancel @{bg background}|
-------------------------------------

(Things you can click on are marked @{bg fill}like this@{bg background}.)

@{b}Image:@{ub}  This donates what image will be used for the map graphic.  When you
select @{" Okay " link "WProjectMenu" 0} from the Project menu in the World Map Editor, the image will
be  converted  into  the  special  FUBAR file format, so you do not need to
distribute  the  exact  image  from  your hard disk (or whatever) with your
World.  Click the "?" to bring up a file requester.

NOTE:   When  the  Import Graphic option is selected, it will automatically
invoke a file requester.

@{b}Use  Files  Palette@{ub}:  If this is enabled, the palette - if it exists and is
valid - will be extracted from the image file and utilised.  Otherwise, the
palette that is currently on the screen at the time will be used instead.

NOTE:   You  can also load palettes from other files by using the  Palette 
editor.

@{b}Adapt Screen:@{ub}  If this is enabled, the World Map Screen will be made so it
can match the screen mode and depth of when the original image was created.

@{i}BETA  NOTE:  If the screen is much larger than the visible area, you cannot
scroll around it yet (until that damn autoscrolling thing works!  :).  Also
this,  like the rest of the program, hasn't been tested with graphics cards
-  let  alone  images  that  were created on a graphics card, yeech!  If it
doesn't  work,  then  it  doesn't  work  -  I'll fix this at a later stage,
because  we  are really concentrating on getting the game running on AGA at
least for now :).  Just use mode promotion if your fussy :)@{ui}

@{b}Import:@{ub}   Gives  the  program the "okay" to attempt to load the image.  Any
previous image will be erased.

@{b}Cancel:@{ub}  Forgets that this operation was ever called.

@endnode

@node "WCountryMenu" "World Editor's Country Menus"

@{b}Create Country@{ub}
This  will  create  a  new  country  on the @{" World " link "WhatIsWorld" 0} map.  It opens the same
dialog  box  as  @{b}Edit  Country@{ub}  would,  so  refer  to Edit Country for more
information.

If the CC cannot add another (for whatever reason) you will be told.  Also,
if you do not give the country a name, the CC will cancel the creation.

@{b}Edit Country@{ub}
First selecting this function, the CC will prompt to you select a @{" country " link "Country" 0}
to edit.  Pick one from the list and choose Okay.

@{i}BETA  NOTE:  I will change this so you can just double-click on the country
on the map.  First things first...  :)@{ui}

See  @{" here " link "WMapEdCnt" 0}  for  more  information  on the Edit Country dialog box and its
functions.

@{b}Delete Country@{ub}
Selecting  this  will  open  a  window prompting you to select a country to
delete.   Once  you  have  selected  a  country,  the  CC  will confirm the
deletion.

@endnode

